sSyiBootTime.name: sSyiBootTime
sSyiBootTime.description: The date and time when the system was booted. This value is in the form dd-mmm-yyyy hh:mm:ss.cc.

sSyiVersion.name: sSyiVersion
sSyiVersion.description: The software version number of the OpenVMS operating system running on the node.

sSyiMemSize.name: sSyiMemSize
sSyiMemSize.description: The total number of pages of physical memory in the system configuration. This value is static.

sSyiAvailCpuCnt.name: sSyiAvailCpuCnt
sSyiAvailCpuCnt.description: The number of CPUs which were available at system bootstrap. This value is static.

sSyiPgSize.name: sSyiPgSize
sSyiPgSize.description: The number of pages in the currently installed page files.

sSyiPgFree.name: sSyiPgFree
sSyiPgFree.description: The number of free pages in the currently installed page files.

sSyiPgUsedPercent.name: sSyiPgUsedPercent
sSyiPgUsedPercent.description: The percent full of the currently installed page files.

sSyiSwpSize.name: sSyiSwpSize
sSyiSwpSize.description: The number of pages in the currently installed swapping files.

sSyiSwpFree.name: sSyiSwpFree
sSyiSwpFree.description: The number of free pages in the currently installed swapping files.

sSyiSwpUsedPercent.name: sSyiSwpUsedPercent
sSyiSwpUsedPercent.description: The percent full of the currently installed swapping files.

sSyiCpuPgSize.name: sSyiCpuPgSize
sSyiCpuPgSize.description: The number of CPU-specific bytes per page in the system. On VAX systems, this value is always 512. On Alpha systems, CPU page size varies from system to system.

sSyiTime.name: sSyiTime
sSyiTime.description: Subagent up time (sCfgUpTime) when system information (sSyi) was last gathered. sCfgSysInfoTimer controls how often system statistics are gathered.

sSyiMemFreePg.name: sSyiMemFreePg
sSyiMemFreePg.description: Number of free pages of physical memory on the system.

sCpuPercentUsed.name: sCpuPercentUsed
sCpuPercentUsed.description: The percent utilization of all CPUs, i.e., the percent of time the combined CPUs were not idle during the last one minute interval.

sIntPercentUsed.name: sIntPercentUsed
sIntPercentUsed.description: The percent of time the combined CPUs spent in interrupt mode during the last one minute interval.

sCpuTicks.name: sCpuTicks
sCpuTicks.description: Number of interval timer ticks that have occurred since the last time CPU statistics were gathered (approximately one minute). This value is the sum of the one minute mode tick counters. This number has been normalized to account for all active CPUs on the system. This value may be used with the one minute CPU mode times to determine the percent of time spent in each CPU mode.

sKernelOne.name: sKernelOne
sKernelOne.description: Time in Kernel mode for all CPUs during the last one minute interval. This value indicates the number of ticks in kernel mode on the kernel stack, when no spinlock busy wait is active.

sExecOne.name: sExecOne
sExecOne.description: Number of interval timer ticks in Executive mode for all CPUs during the last one minute interval.

sSuprOne.name: sSuprOne
sSuprOne.description: Number of interval timer ticks in Supervisor mode for all CPUs during the last one minute interval.

sUserOne.name: sUserOne
sUserOne.description: Number of interval timer ticks in User mode for all CPUs during the last one minute interval.

sIntrOne.name: sIntrOne
sIntrOne.description: Time in Interrupt mode for all CPUs during the last one minute interval. This value indicates the number of interval timer ticks in Kernel mode on the Interrupt stack.

sCompOne.name: sCompOne
sCompOne.description: Number of interval timer ticks in Compatibility mode for all CPUs during the last one minute interval.

sSpinOne.name: sSpinOne
sSpinOne.description: Number of interval timer ticks in mpsynch mode (i.e., Kernel mode on kernel or interrupt stack, when spinlock busy wait is active) for all CPUs during the last one minute interval.

sNullOne.name: sNullOne
sNullOne.description: CPU idle time for all CPUs during the last one minute interval. This value is measured in interval timer ticks.

sKernelFive.name: sKernelFive
sKernelFive.description: Number of ticks spent in Kernel mode during the past five minutes.

sExecFive.name: sExecFive
sExecFive.description: Number of ticks spent in Executive mode during the past five minutes.

sSuprFive.name: sSuprFive
sSuprFive.description: Number of ticks spent in Supervisor mode during the past five minutes.

sUserFive.name: sUserFive
sUserFive.description: Number of ticks spent in User mode during the past five minutes.

sIntrFive.name: sIntrFive
sIntrFive.description: Number of ticks spent in Interrupt mode during the past five minutes.

sCompFive.name: sCompFive
sCompFive.description: Number of ticks spent in Compatibility mode during the past five minutes.

sSpinFive.name: sSpinFive
sSpinFive.description: Number of ticks spent in Spin mode during the past five minutes.

sNullFive.name: sNullFive
sNullFive.description: Number of ticks the CPUs were idle during the past five minutes.

sKernelFifteen.name: sKernelFifteen
sKernelFifteen.description: Number of ticks spent in Kernel mode during the past fifteen minutes.

sExecFifteen.name: sExecFifteen
sExecFifteen.description: Number of ticks spent in Executive mode during the past fifteen minutes.

sSuprFifteen.name: sSuprFifteen
sSuprFifteen.description: Number of ticks spent in Supervisor mode during the past fifteen minutes.

sUserFifteen.name: sUserFifteen
sUserFifteen.description: Number of ticks spent in User mode during the past fifteen minutes.

sIntrFifteen.name: sIntrFifteen
sIntrFifteen.description: Number of ticks spent in Interrupt mode during the past fifteen minutes.

sCompFifteen.name: sCompFifteen
sCompFifteen.description: Number of ticks spent in Compatibility mode during the past fifteen minutes.

sSpinFifteen.name: sSpinFifteen
sSpinFifteen.description: Number of ticks spent in Spin mode during the past fifteen minutes.

sNullFifteen.name: sNullFifteen
sNullFifteen.description: Number of ticks the CPUs were idle during the past fifteen minutes.

sDskTblCnt.name: sDskTblCnt
sDskTblCnt.description: Number of entries in the disk table.

sDskTblTime.name: sDskTblTime
sDskTblTime.description: Subagent up time (sCfgUpTime) when disk statistics (sDskTbl) were last gathered. sCfgDskTimer controls how often disk statistics are gathered.

sDskEntry.name: sDskEntry
sDskEntry.description: A row in the disk table.

sDskOps.name: sDskOps
sDskOps.description: The average number of disk operations per second during the last disk statistics update interval. (The disk statistics update frequency is determined by the variable sCfgDskTimer.)

sDskMountCnt.name: sDskMountCnt
sDskMountCnt.description: The mount count for the volume.

sDskRefCnt.name: sDskRefCnt
sDskRefCnt.description: The number of channels assigned to the device.

sDskTransCnt.name: sDskTransCnt
sDskTransCnt.description: The transaction count for the volume.

sDskMediaName.name: sDskMediaName
sDskMediaName.description: The name of the volume type.

sDskOpCnt.name: sDskOpCnt
sDskOpCnt.description: The operation count for the volume.

sDskFreeBlocks.name: sDskFreeBlocks
sDskFreeBlocks.description: The number of free blocks on the disk.

sDskMaxBlocks.name: sDskMaxBlocks
sDskMaxBlocks.description: The maximum number of blocks on the volume.

sDskStatus.name: sDskStatus
sDskStatus.description: The device unit status for the physical disk or virtual disk. This value is a bit vector which, when set, corresponds to the following states: Bit Description 0 TIM (time-out is enabled) 1 INT (Interrupt is expected) 2 ERLOGIP (Error log in progress on unit) 3 CANCEL (I/O on unit is canceled) 4 ONLINE (Unit is online) 5 POWER (Power failed while unit busy) 6 TIMOUT (Unit timed out) 7 INTTYPE (Receiver interrupt) 8 BSY (Unit is busy) 9 MOUNTING (Device is being mounted) 10 DEADMO (Deallocate at dismount) 11 VALID (Volume is software valid) 12 UNLOAD (Unload volume at dismount) 13 TEMPLATE (Template UCB) 14 MNTVERIP (Mount verification is in progress) 15 WRONGVOL (Wrong volume detected during mount verification) 16 DELETEUCB (Delete this UCB when reference count equals 0) 17 LCL_VALID (Volume is valid on local node) 18 SUPMVMSG (Suppress mount verification messages if they indicate success) 19 MNTVERPEND (Mount verification is pending on the device and the device is busy) 20 DISMOUNT (Dismount in progress) 21 CLUTRAN (VAXcluster state transition in progress) 22 WRTLOCKMV (Write-locked mount verification in progress) 23 SVPN_END (Last byte used from page is mapped by a system virtual page number ) 24 ALTBSY (Unit is busy via an alternate startup path) 25 SNAPSHOT (Restart verification is in progress) A sDskStatus trap message is sent when a device transitions into the POWER, TIMOUT, or MNTVERIP state.

sDskDevChar.name: sDskDevChar
sDskDevChar.description: The disk device-independent characteristics of the disk. This value is a bit vector which, when set, corresponds to the following characteristic: Bit Description 0 REC (Device is record oriented) 1 CCL (Device is a carriage control device) 2 TRM (Device is a terminal) 3 DIR (Device is directory structured) 4 SDI (Device is single-directory structured) 5 SQD (Device is sequential and block oriented) 6 SPL (Device is being spooled) 7 OPR (Device is an operator) 8 RCT (Disk contains Revector Cache Table. This bit is set for every DAA disk) 13 NET (Device is a network device) 14 FOD (Device is files oriented) 15 DUA (Device is dual ported) 16 SHR (Device is shareable) 17 GEN (Device is a generic device) 18 AVL (Device is available for use) 19 MNT (Device is mounted) 20 MBX (Device is a mailbox) 21 DMT (Device is marked for dismount) 22 ELG (Device has error logging enabled) 23 ALL (Device is allocated) 24 FOR (Device is mounted foreign) 25 SWL (Devoce is software write locked) 26 IDV (Device can provide input) 27 ODV (Device can provide output) 28 RND (Device allows random access) 29 RTM (Device is a real-time device) 30 RCK (Device has read-checking enabled) 31 WCK (Device has write-checking enabled)

sDskLogVolName.name: sDskLogVolName
sDskLogVolName.description: The logical name of the volume or volume set.

sDskTrapPercent.name: sDskTrapPercent
sDskTrapPercent.description: The percentage of disk space utilization at which excessive disk utilization (sDskFull) traps begin to be sent for this disk. A value of 0 indicates that either a disk block free count is being used for this disk (see sDskTrapBlocks), or the system default disk use limit (identified by sCfgDskLimit), or the system default disk minimum free block limit (identified by sCfgDskMinFreeBlks) for the system is being used. Disks which have a specific usage limit set are contained in the critical disk file. See sCfgCritDsk for more information about this file.

sDskTrapBlocks.name: sDskTrapBlocks
sDskTrapBlocks.description: The minimum number of free disk blocks required for this disk. If the actual number of free blocks on the disk drops below this level, disk utilization (sDskFull) traps begin to be sent for this disk. A value of 0 indicates that either a percent full is being used for this disk (see sDskTrapPercent) or the system default disk use limit (identified by sCfgDskLimit), or the system default disk minimum free block limit (identified by sCfgDskMinFreeBlks) for the system is being used. Disks which have a specific usage limit set are contained in the critical disk file. See sCfgCritDsk for more information about this file.

sDskShdCount.name: sDskShdCount
sDskShdCount.description: The number of shadow set members that make up this virtual unit. If this number is zero, then this is not a virtual disk. This number indicates the number of shadow set entries that will be found in the (sShdTbl) for this disk.

sDskTrapOpSec.name: sDskTrapOpSec
sDskTrapOpSec.description: The number of operations per second at which excessive disk (sDskOpSec) traps begin to be sent for this disk. A value of 0 indicates that the system default disk operations per second limit (identified by sCfgDskOps), is being used. Disks which have a specific limit set are contained in the critical disk file. If both this value and sCfgDskOps are zero, disk operations per second traps are disabled. See sCfgCritDsk for more information about the critical disk file.

sDskQueueLength.name: sDskQueueLength
sDskQueueLength.description: I/O queue length for this disk.

sDskRemote.name: sDskRemote
sDskRemote.description: A value of true(1) indicates that the device is a remote device; a value of false(2) indicates that it is not a remote device. A remote device is a device that is not directly connected to the local node, but instead is visible through the VMScluster system.

sShdEntry.name: sShdEntry
sShdEntry.description: A row in the shadow table. The combination of the sDskIndex and sShdIndex indices relates each shadow set table entry (sShdEntry) to its virtual unit entry in the disk table (sDskTbl).

sShdIndex.name: sShdIndex
sShdIndex.description: Location in the shadow set table.

sShdName.name: sShdName
sShdName.description: Device name of the shadow set disk.

sShdFail.name: sShdFail
sShdFail.description: Indicator for shadow set member failure. A value of true(1) indicates that this member has failed out of the shadow set.

sShdCopy.name: sShdCopy
sShdCopy.description: Indicator for shadow set catch-up copying. A value of true(1) indicates that this member is in a catch-up copy state.

sShdMerge.name: sShdMerge
sShdMerge.description: Indicator for shadow set member merge. A value of true(1) indicates that this member is in a merge state.

sQueCnt.name: sQueCnt
sQueCnt.description: Number of queues currently being monitored. This number is the number of queue names found in the sCfgQueFile file.

sQueTime.name: sQueTime
sQueTime.description: Subagent up time (sCfgUpTime) when queue statistics (sQTbl) were last gathered. sCfgQueTimer controls how often queue statistics are gathered.

sQTblEntry.name: sQTblEntry
sQTblEntry.description: A row in the queue table.

sQMonitor.name: sQMonitor
sQMonitor.description: Indicates if the queue and its entries are currently being monitored. A value of true(1) indicates that this queue and its entries are currently being monitored. A value of false(2) indicates that monitoring is currently disabled on this queue and its entries.

sQStatus.name: sQStatus
sQStatus.description: Queue status indicates the current settings of the queue status flags. This value is a bit vector which, when set, corresponds to the following characteristic: Bit Description 0 Queue is aligning 1 Queue is idle: no jobs executing and none available for execution 2 Lowercase device 3 Queue is doing /OPERATOR (intentionally not documented) 4 Queue is paused 5 Queue is pausing 6 Remote device 7 Incomplete remote request to reset (OBSOLETE) 8 Queue is resuming from paused state 9 /DEVICE=SERVER or reported to be a served queue by the symbiont 10 Device is stalled 11 Queue is starting 12 Queue is stopped 13 Queue is stopping 14 Device is unavailable 15 Queue is closed 16 Queue is executing as many jobs as it is capable of executing 17 Queue does not yet exist in db or is being removed from db 18 At least one job is executing, but the queue is capable of executing more 19 Queue is not able to accept or process jobs; its QSIs are inactive 20 AUTOSTART queue explicitly stopped 21 Queue will be stopped when work currently in progress has completed

sQEntryCount.name: sQEntryCount
sQEntryCount.description: Number of current queue entries. This number also identifies the number of rows in the sQEntryTbl for this queue.

sQEntry.name: sQEntry
sQEntry.description: A row in the queue entry table.

sQEntryNum.name: sQEntryNum
sQEntryNum.description: The queue entry number of this job.

sQEntryJobname.name: sQEntryJobname
sQEntryJobname.description: The job name of this queue entry.

sQEntryJobStatus.name: sQEntryJobStatus
sQEntryJobStatus.description: Queue status indicates the current settings of the queue status flags. This value is a bit vector which, when set, corresponds to the following characteristic: Bit Description 0 Job is aborting 1 Job is executing 2 Job is holding for /HOLD 3 Job is inaccessible 4 Job was refused by symbiont 5 Job will requeue after abort (intentionally not documented) 6 Job started execution at least once (intentionally not documented) 7 Job was retained by /RETAIN 8 Job is starting 9 Job is holding for /AFTER 10 Job is suspended by STOP/QUEUE command 11 Job is pending 12 Job does not yet exist in db or is being removed from db 13 Current job on stalled queue 14 Job was processed by the symbiont but further processing is necessary 15 Job has been completely processed

sQueBatchPending.name: sQueBatchPending
sQueBatchPending.description: Number of pending jobs in the batch queue.

sQueBatchExecuting.name: sQueBatchExecuting
sQueBatchExecuting.description: Number of executing jobs in the batch queue.

sQueBatchTimed.name: sQueBatchTimed
sQueBatchTimed.description: Number of timed jobs in the batch queue.

sQueBatchHolding.name: sQueBatchHolding
sQueBatchHolding.description: Number of holding jobs in the batch queue.

sQueBatchRetained.name: sQueBatchRetained
sQueBatchRetained.description: Number of retained jobs in the batch queue.

sQueGenericPending.name: sQueGenericPending
sQueGenericPending.description: Number of pending jobs in generic queues.

sQueGenericExecuting.name: sQueGenericExecuting
sQueGenericExecuting.description: Number of executing jobs in generic queues.

sQueGenericTimed.name: sQueGenericTimed
sQueGenericTimed.description: Number of timed jobs in generic queues.

sQueGenericHolding.name: sQueGenericHolding
sQueGenericHolding.description: Number of holding jobs in generic queues.

sQueGenericRetained.name: sQueGenericRetained
sQueGenericRetained.description: Number of retained jobs in generic queues.

sQuePrinterPending.name: sQuePrinterPending
sQuePrinterPending.description: Number of pending jobs in printer queues.

sQuePrinterExecuting.name: sQuePrinterExecuting
sQuePrinterExecuting.description: Number of executing jobs in printer queues.

sQuePrinterTimed.name: sQuePrinterTimed
sQuePrinterTimed.description: Number of timed jobs in printer queues.

sQuePrinterHolding.name: sQuePrinterHolding
sQuePrinterHolding.description: Number of holding jobs in printer queues.

sQuePrinterRetained.name: sQuePrinterRetained
sQuePrinterRetained.description: Number of retained jobs in printer queues.

sQueServerPending.name: sQueServerPending
sQueServerPending.description: Number of pending jobs in server queues.

sQueServerExecuting.name: sQueServerExecuting
sQueServerExecuting.description: Number of executing jobs in server queues.

sQueServerTimed.name: sQueServerTimed
sQueServerTimed.description: Number of timed jobs in server queues.

sQueServerHolding.name: sQueServerHolding
sQueServerHolding.description: Number of holding jobs in server queues.

sQueServerRetained.name: sQueServerRetained
sQueServerRetained.description: Number of retained jobs in server queues.

sQueSymbiontPending.name: sQueSymbiontPending
sQueSymbiontPending.description: Number of pending jobs in symbiont queues.

sQueSymbiontExecuting.name: sQueSymbiontExecuting
sQueSymbiontExecuting.description: Number of executing jobs in symbiont queues.

sQueSymbiontTimed.name: sQueSymbiontTimed
sQueSymbiontTimed.description: Number of timed jobs in symbiont queues.

sQueSymbiontHolding.name: sQueSymbiontHolding
sQueSymbiontHolding.description: Number of holding jobs in symbiont queues.

sQueSymbiontRetained.name: sQueSymbiontRetained
sQueSymbiontRetained.description: Number of retained jobs in symbiont queues.

sQueTerminalPending.name: sQueTerminalPending
sQueTerminalPending.description: Number of pending jobs in terminal queues.

sQueTerminalExecuting.name: sQueTerminalExecuting
sQueTerminalExecuting.description: Number of executing jobs in terminal queues.

sQueTerminalTimed.name: sQueTerminalTimed
sQueTerminalTimed.description: Number of timed jobs in terminal queues.

sQueTerminalHolding.name: sQueTerminalHolding
sQueTerminalHolding.description: Number of holding jobs in terminal queues.

sQueTerminalRetained.name: sQueTerminalRetained
sQueTerminalRetained.description: Number of retained jobs in terminal queues.

sQManCount.name: sQManCount
sQManCount.description: Number of entries in the queue manager table.

sQManTblEntry.name: sQManTblEntry
sQManTblEntry.description: A row in the queue manager table.

sQManIndex.name: sQManIndex
sQManIndex.description: Location in the queue manager table.

sQManStatus.name: sQManStatus
sQManStatus.description: Queue manager status indicates the current settings of the queue manger status flags. This value is a bit vector which, when set, corresponds to the following characteristic: Bit Description 0 Start pending 1 Starting 2 Running 3 Failover 4 Stopping 5 Stopped

sPsCnt.name: sPsCnt
sPsCnt.description: Number of processes currently running of the system.

sPsTime.name: sPsTime
sPsTime.description: Subagent up time (sCfgUpTime) when process statistics (sPsTbl) were last gathered. sCfgPsTimer controls how often process statistics are gathered.

sPsEntry.name: sPsEntry
sPsEntry.description: A row in the process table.

sPsPID.name: sPsPID
sPsPID.description: The VMS process identification (PID) of the process.

sPsPriority.name: sPsPriority
sPsPriority.description: The current priority of the process.

sPsDirectIO.name: sPsDirectIO
sPsDirectIO.description: The count of the direct I/O operations performed by this process. If sCfgAllPsData is set to no(2), this value may be zero.

sPsCpuTime.name: sPsCpuTime
sPsCpuTime.description: The process' accumulated CPU time. If sCfgAllPsData is set to no(2), this value may be zero.

sPsPgFaults.name: sPsPgFaults
sPsPgFaults.description: The total number of page faults incurred by the process. If sCfgAllPsData is set to no(2), this value may be zero.

sPsWorkSetSize.name: sPsWorkSetSize
sPsWorkSetSize.description: The current working set size (in pages) of the process. If sCfgAllPsData is set to no(2), this value may be zero.

sPsUsername.name: sPsUsername
sPsUsername.description: The owner username of the process. This string is always blank padded to a length of 12 characters.

sPsPhysTerm.name: sPsPhysTerm
sPsPhysTerm.description: The physical device name of the terminal associated with the process.

sPsImageName.name: sPsImageName
sPsImageName.description: The directory specification and image file name. If sCfgAllPsData is set to no(2), this value may be zero.

sPsLoginTime.name: sPsLoginTime
sPsLoginTime.description: The time at which the process was created. This value is in dd-mmm-yyyy hh:mm:ss.cc format. If sCfgAllPsData is set to no(2), this value may be zero.

sPsPgTblCnt.name: sPsPgTblCnt
sPsPgTblCnt.description: The number of pages the process has in its working set.

sPsRWState.name: sPsRWState
sPsRWState.description: The resource wait state of the process. This variable is only meaningful when a process is in the MWAIT state (i.e., when sPsState is set to MWAIT(2)), otherwise this variable contains no data. The above listed resource wait states have the following meanings: AST - AST wait MBX - Mailbox full NPG - Nonpaged dynamic memory PFF - Page file full PAG - Paged dynamic memory MPE - Modified page list empty MPB - Modified page writer busy SCS - Distributed lock manager wait CLU - VMScluster transition CAP - CPU capability CSV - VMScluster server process PSXFRK - POSIX fork creation MUTEX - Locked resource

sPsCOMQueue.name: sPsCOMQueue
sPsCOMQueue.description: Number of processes that are waiting to compute, i.e., the number of processes with a sPsState of COM.

sPsCOMOQueue.name: sPsCOMOQueue
sPsCOMOQueue.description: Number of outswapped processes that are waiting to compute, i.e., the number of processes with a sPsState of COMO.

sPsOther.name: sPsOther
sPsOther.description: Count of other mode processes i.e., those processes that are not network, batch or interactive.

sCritCnt.name: sCritCnt
sCritCnt.description: Number of critical process table entries.

sCritTime.name: sCritTime
sCritTime.description: Subagent up time (sCfgUpTime) when critical process statistics (sCritTbl) were last gathered. sCfgCritTimer specifies how often critical process statistics are gathered.

sCritEntry.name: sCritEntry
sCritEntry.description: A row in the critical process table.

sCritIndex.name: sCritIndex
sCritIndex.description: Location in the critical process table.

sCritName.name: sCritName
sCritName.description: Name of a critical process. Critical process names may contain * and % wildcard characters.

sCritReqCnt.name: sCritReqCnt
sCritReqCnt.description: Minimum number of copies of this process required to be running on the system.

sCritCurCnt.name: sCritCurCnt
sCritCurCnt.description: The current number of copies of this process running on the system.

sTrapNextSeqNum.name: sTrapNextSeqNum
sTrapNextSeqNum.description: The next sequence number in the trap table. When this variable is sent as part of a trap, it identifies the sequence number assigned to that trap. This is a 32-bit value and will wrap after 4294967295.

sTrapTime.name: sTrapTime
sTrapTime.description: Subagent up time (sCfgUpTime) when the trap was created.

sTrapResendSeqNum.name: sTrapResendSeqNum
sTrapResendSeqNum.description: Sequence number of a trap message to be resent to the manager. Setting this variable to a trap sequence number causes the specified trap message to be resent. If the set-request contains a number that is not available (the number of items retained in the trap table is dependent on the value of sCfgTrapTblSize), an error indicator will be returned.

sTrapLastSeqNumSent.name: sTrapLastSeqNumSent
sTrapLastSeqNumSent.description: Sequence number of the last trap sent. This value may be compared to sTrapNextSeqNum to determine if a backlog of traps exists. If this value is one less than sTrapNextSeqNum, then no backlog exists. A backlog of traps may exist if more traps are generated per second than may be sent (as specified by the variable sCfgMaxTrapSec).

sTrapLostCount.name: sTrapLostCount
sTrapLostCount.description: This variable indicates the number of traps that have been lost. A trap is considered to be lost if it is overwritten in the internal trap table before it is sent to the NMS. This may occur if the trap table is not large enough (see sCfgTrapTblSize) to hold all of unsent traps. How quickly traps are sent to the NMS is governed by the sCfgMaxTrapSec variable. To prevent trap loss, set these two variables so that the trap backlog does not overflow the trap table and so that traps do not flood the network.

sHwErrTime.name: sHwErrTime
sHwErrTime.description: Subagent up time (sCfgUpTime) when hardware error statistics were last gathered.

sHwErrEntry.name: sHwErrEntry
sHwErrEntry.description: A row in the hardware error table.

sHwErrIndex.name: sHwErrIndex
sHwErrIndex.description: Location in the hardware error table.

sHwErrCnt.name: sHwErrCnt
sHwErrCnt.description: Number of errors reported by the device since last reboot of the system.

sHwErrLastTime.name: sHwErrLastTime
sHwErrLastTime.description: sCfgUpTime when the latest error was detected by the NM*SysMgr Subagent.

sSwErrFile.name: sSwErrFile
sSwErrFile.description: The file name of the software element which generated the latest software status code.

sSwErrLineNum.name: sSwErrLineNum
sSwErrLineNum.description: The line number in the file which generated the latest software status code.

sSwErrLastTime.name: sSwErrLastTime
sSwErrLastTime.description: sCfgUpTime when the most recent software status code was generated.

sSwErrMessage.name: sSwErrMessage
sSwErrMessage.description: Description of the latest software error.

sOpcomOne.name: sOpcomOne
sOpcomOne.description: The first 255 characters of the text of the most recent message in the operator log. For opcom messages that exceed 255 characters, the remainder of the message will be contained in sOpcomTwo, sOpcomThree, sOpcomFour, sOpcomFive, sOpcomSix, and sOpcomSeven depending on the length of the message. All operator log messages are sent as sOpcomMessage traps and retained in the internal trap table. To retrieve a previous message, resend the trap (see sTrapResendSeqNum).

sOpcomReplyId.name: sOpcomReplyId
sOpcomReplyId.description: Request number to be associated with the operator reply. This number identifies a previous Opcom request. This variable is reset to zero when a reply is successfully sent. (See sOpcomReplySend.)

sOpcomReplyStatus.name: sOpcomReplyStatus
sOpcomReplyStatus.description: Completion status to accompany opcom reply. This variable is reset to noStatus when a reply is successfully sent. (See sOpcomReplySend.)

sOpcomReplyText.name: sOpcomReplyText
sOpcomReplyText.description: Text to be sent for an operator reply message. This variable is reset to null when a reply is successfully sent. (See sOpcomReplySend.)

sOpcomReplySend.name: sOpcomReplySend
sOpcomReplySend.description: Flag which is used to trigger sending of an operator reply message. To send an operator reply, set the sOpcomReplyId, sOpcomReplyStatus, and sOpcomReplyText variables and then set the sOpcomReplySend to true. All opcom reply variables will be reset following a successful send.

sCfgFile.name: sCfgFile
sCfgFile.description: Name of the file currently being used for NM*SysMgr initialization parameters. This file is identified by the logical name COMTEK$SYSMGR_CONFIG. Changing this variable redefines the COMTEK$SYSMGR_CONFIG logical name. NM*SysMgr must be reinitialized (by setting the variable sCfgReinitSubagent to true) before the new configuration file is used. If a set-request is performed on this variable and the specified file name does not exist, is not accessible by the subagent, or contains invalid data, the file name is not changed, and an error is returned, and a sSwErr trap is generated describing the error. Set-requests: Take effect only after reinitialization (sCfgReinitSubagent) NOTE: To make changes to this value permanent across system reboots, the definition of this logical name must also be changed in the system startup procedures.

sCfgLogFile.name: sCfgLogFile
sCfgLogFile.description: Name of the log file currently being used by NM*SysMgr. If this process is run interactively, this variable will have the value SYS$OUTPUT: (standard output).

sCfgCritFile.name: sCfgCritFile
sCfgCritFile.description: Name of the file currently being used to identify critical processes. This file is associated with the logical name COMTEK$SYSMGR_CRITPROC. Changing this variable redefines the COMTEK$SYSMGR_CRITPROC logical name. NM*SysMgr must be reinitialized (by setting the variable sCfgReinitSubagent to true) before the new critical process file is used. If a set-request is performed on this variable and the specified file name does not exist, is not accessible by the subagent, or contains invalid data, the file name is not changed, an error is returned, and a sSwErr trap is generated describing the error. Set-requests: Take effect only after reinitialization (sCfgReinitSubagent) NOTE: To make changes to this value permanent across system reboots, the definition of this logical name must also be changed in the system startup procedures.

sCfgReinitSubagent.name: sCfgReinitSubagent
sCfgReinitSubagent.description: Flag which may be set to force the NM*SysMgr Subagent to reinitialize. Reinitialization involves resetting the process configuration using the parameters contained in the sCfgFile and resetting the critical process, critical disk, and critical queue data as specified in the sCfgCritFile, sCfgCritDsk, and sCfgCritQue files and sending the sWarmStart trap.

sCfgTraps.name: sCfgTraps
sCfgTraps.description: Flag which determines if any trap messages are sent to the NM*Master Agent. Setting this variable to disabled(2) disables all traps from being sent. Configuration Variable: Traps Set-requests: Take effect immediately Changes to this value are written to the sCfgFile.

sCfgHwErrTraps.name: sCfgHwErrTraps
sCfgHwErrTraps.description: Flag which determines if hardware error traps (sHwErr) should be sent. Setting this variable to enabled(1) causes a trap to be sent for every error detected. Setting this variable to disabled(2) disables hardware error traps from being sent. Configuration Variable: HwErrTrap Set-requests: Take effect immediately Changes to this value are written to the sCfgFile.

sCfgCpuLimit.name: sCfgCpuLimit
sCfgCpuLimit.description: The percentage of CPU utilization at which excessive CPU utilization (sCpuUsage) traps begin to be sent. A value of 0 disables these traps. Configuration Variable: CpuUtil Set-requests: Take effect immediately Changes to this value are written to the sCfgFile.

sCfgIntLimit.name: sCfgIntLimit
sCfgIntLimit.description: The percentage of interrupt CPU utilization at which excessive interrupt utilization (sIntUsage) traps begin to be sent. A value of 0 disables these traps. Configuration Variable: IntUtil Set-requests: Take effect immediately Changes to this value are written to the sCfgFile.

sCfgDskOps.name: sCfgDskOps
sCfgDskOps.description: The threshold at which excessive disk busy traps (sDskOpSec) begin to be sent. This value is expressed in terms of disk operations (reads and writes) per second. At expiration of each sCfgDskTimer interval, the number of disk operations during the intervening interval is computed. A trap is sent if the number of operations during that interval exceeds the this limit. A value of 0 disables disk busy traps. Different thresholds may be set on individual disks by specifying an OpSec limit in the critical disk file. Configuration Variable: DskOps Set-requests: Take effect immediately Changes to this value are written to the sCfgFile.

sCfgDskLimit.name: sCfgDskLimit
sCfgDskLimit.description: The percentage of disk space utilization at which excessive disk utilization (sDskFull) traps begin to be sent. If this variable is set to a value other than zero, it is used to determine when to send sDskFull traps for disks not specified in the critical disk table (see sCfgCritDsk). This value and sCfgDskMinFreeBlks are mutually exclusive, i.e., only one of these values is in effect at any given time. If neither value is specified in the configuration file, then the default value of sCfgDskLimit is used for disk monitoring and sCfgDskMinFreeBlks is set to zero. To disable default disk full monitoring, both of these values must be zero. Set-requests to this value will fail unless sCfgDskMinFreeBlks is set to zero. Configuration Variable: DskUse Set-requests: Take effect immediately Changes to this value are written to the sCfgFile.

sCfgPgLimit.name: sCfgPgLimit
sCfgPgLimit.description: The percentage of page file utilization at which excessive page file utilization (sPgFull) traps begin to be sent. A value of 0 disables these traps. Configuration Variable: PgUse Set-requests: Take effect immediately Changes to this value are written to the sCfgFile.

sCfgSwpLimit.name: sCfgSwpLimit
sCfgSwpLimit.description: The percentage of swap file utilization at which excessive swap file utilization (sSwpFull) traps begin to be sent. A value of 0 disables these traps. Configuration Variable: SwpUse Set-requests: Take effect immediately Changes to this value are written to the sCfgFile.

sCfgPsTimer.name: sCfgPsTimer
sCfgPsTimer.description: The number of minutes between updates of the process statistics table (sPsTbl) data. A value of 0 disables gathering of process related data. Configuration Variable: PsTimer Set-requests: Take effect on next timer expiration Changes to this value are written to the sCfgFile.

sCfgDskTimer.name: sCfgDskTimer
sCfgDskTimer.description: The number of minutes between updates of the disk table (sDskTbl) data. A value of 0 disables gathering of disk related data. Configuration Variable: DskTimer Set-requests: Take effect on next timer expiration Changes to this value are written to the sCfgFile.

sCfgHwErrTimer.name: sCfgHwErrTimer
sCfgHwErrTimer.description: The number of minutes between updates of the hardware error table (sHwErrTbl) data. A value of 0 disables gathering of hardware error data. Configuration Variable: HwErrTimer Set-requests: Take effect on next timer expiration Changes to this value are written to the sCfgFile.

sCfgSysInfoTimer.name: sCfgSysInfoTimer
sCfgSysInfoTimer.description: The number of minutes between updates of the system information (sSyi) data. A value of 0 disables gathering of system information data. Configuration Variable: SysInfoTimer Set-requests: Take effect on next timer expiration Changes to this value are written to the sCfgFile.

sCfgCritTimer.name: sCfgCritTimer
sCfgCritTimer.description: The number of minutes between critical process table (sCritTbl) updates. A value of 0 disables critical process missing processing. Configuration Variable: CritTimer Set-requests: Take effect on next timer expiration Changes to this value are written to the sCfgFile.

sCfgDskAlarm.name: sCfgDskAlarm
sCfgDskAlarm.description: The number of minutes between repeat traps for disk (sDskFull), page file (sPgFull), or swap file full (sSwpFull) conditions. A value of 0 causes only the initial instance of the disk, page file, or swap file full condition to trigger a trap. Configuration Variable: RptDskAlarm Set-requests: Take effect on next timer expiration Changes to this value are written to the sCfgFile.

sCfgCritAlarm.name: sCfgCritAlarm
sCfgCritAlarm.description: The number of minutes between repeat traps for a given critical process missing condition. Setting this variable to 0 causes only the first instance to generate a trap. Configuration Variable: RptCritAlarm Set-requests: Take effect on next timer expiration Changes to this value are written to the sCfgFile.

sCfgTrapTblSize.name: sCfgTrapTblSize
sCfgTrapTblSize.description: The maximum number of traps to be retained. Traps that are retained may be resent (see sTrapResendSeqNum) unless too many subsequent traps have been generated. This variable controls how many traps are retained in NM*SysMgr's internal trap table. Configuration Variable: TrapTableSize Set-Requests: Take effect immediately Changes to this value are written to the sCfgFile.

sCfgHostName.name: sCfgHostName
sCfgHostName.description: The name of the host that the subagent is communicating with. This is the host name where the NM*Master Agent resides. This variable is not currently used. Configuration Variable: Host

sCfgAllPsData.name: sCfgAllPsData
sCfgAllPsData.description: This variable controls the amount of data that is available in the process statistics table (sPsTbl). If this flag is set to no(2), only the process statistics that are contained in the process control block (PCB) or job information block (JIB) for each process are available (data in the process header (PHD) may also be available). Setting this flag to yes makes all statistics in the sPsTbl available but incurs an additional performance overhead (to retrieve out swapped processes and deliver kernel mode ASTs to all processes). Configuration variable: AllPsData Set-requests: Take effect immediately. Changes to this value are written to the sCfgFile.

sCfgTimeout.name: sCfgTimeout
sCfgTimeout.description: This variable identifies the time-out value that is to be used by the subagent during subtree registration. If this value is set to zero, the default value (saDefaultTimeout) contained in the NM*Master Agent will be used. If the value specified exceeds the current maximum that NM*Master will permit (saMaxTimeout), the maximum value will be used. This value is specified in seconds. Configuration Variable: Timeout

sCfgOpcomSecurity.name: sCfgOpcomSecurity
sCfgOpcomSecurity.description: Flag which determines if the opcom security messages are to be sent as opcom traps. Setting this variable to enabled(1) causes opcom trap messages to be sent for security messages. Configuration Variable: OpcomSecurity Set-requests: Take effect at next process start-up Changes to this value are written to the tCfgFile.

sCfgControlTermProc.name: sCfgControlTermProc
sCfgControlTermProc.description: Flag which may be used to disable process termination by the sCfgTermProc variable. Setting this variable to enabled(1) allows the sCfgTermProc variable to be set to true(1) to terminate the NM*SysMgr process. Setting this variable to disabled(2) prevents the sCfgTermProc variable from being set. Configuration Variable: ControlTermProc

sCfgTermProc.name: sCfgTermProc
sCfgTermProc.description: Flag which may be used to shutdown the NM*SysMgr process. Setting this flag to true causes the NM*SysMgr process to respond to the set-request, send the sTermProc trap, close the connection to the NM*Master Agent, and shutdown. If the sCfgControlTermProc flag state is disabled(2), the sCfgTermProc variable can not be set. Set-requests: Take effect immediately if sCfgControlTermProc is enabled(2)

sCfgVersion.name: sCfgVersion
sCfgVersion.description: Current version of the NM*SysMgr Subagent software.

sCfgMaxTrapSec.name: sCfgMaxTrapSec
sCfgMaxTrapSec.description: This value specifies the maximum number of traps per second that may be sent. A value of zero disables trap throttling, allowing all traps to be sent as they are generated. It is recommended that this value and sCfgTrapTblSize be tuned to each operational environment. Configuration Variable: MaxTrapSec Set-requests: Take effect immediately. Changes to this value are written to the sCfgFile.

sCfgCritDsk.name: sCfgCritDsk
sCfgCritDsk.description: Name of the file currently being used to identify critical disk space and operations per second trap thresholds for individual disks. This file contains: disk name (required) percent full or number of free blocks (optional) operations per second (optional) The disk name may take the form of a physical disk name (including the leading underscore (_) and trailing colon (:)), a logical volume name, or, for shadowed disks, the name of the virtual unit. If two entries specify the same disk (one by physical name and the other by logical volume name), only the entry for the physcial disk name will be used for that disk. Once the disk usage exceeds the specified percent full or the number of free blocks drops below the specified free disk blocks, disk full (sDskFull) traps will begin to be sent. Disk busy (sDskOpSec) traps are sent if the number of operations per second exceeds the limit specified for this disk. The following are valid entries in the critical disk file: _ALPHA$DKA0:,blocks=652829 disk$alphasys,percent=99,ops=120 _DSA1:,ops=300 This file is associated with the system logical name COMTEK$SYSMGR_CRITDSK. Changing this variable redefines the COMTEK$SYSMGR_CRITDSK logical name. NM*SysMgr must be reinitialized (by setting the variable sCfgReinitSubagent to true) before a new critical disk file is used. If a set-request is performed on this variable and the specified file name does not exist, is not accessible by the subagent, or contains invalid data, the file name is not changed, an error is returned, and a sSwErr trap is generated describing the error. Set-requests: Take effect only after reinitialization (sCfgReinitSubagent) NOTE: To make changes to this value permanent across system reboots, the definition of this logical name must also be changed in the system startup procedures.

sCfgCritQue.name: sCfgCritQue
sCfgCritQue.description: Name of the file currently being used to identify queues to be monitored. This file is associated with the logical name COMTEK$SYSMGR_QUEUE. Changing this variable redefines the COMTEK$SYSMGR_QUEUE logical name. NM*SysMgr must be reinitialized (by setting the variable sCfgReinitSubagent to true) before the new queue file is used. If a set-request is performed on this variable and the specified file name does not exist, is not accessible by the subagent, or contains invalid data, the file name is not changed, an error is returned, and a sSwErr trap is generated describing the error. Set-requests: Take effect only after reinitialization (sCfgReinitSubagent) NOTE: To make changes to this value permanent across system reboots, the definition of this logical name must also be changed in the system startup procedures.

sCfgQueTimer.name: sCfgQueTimer
sCfgQueTimer.description: The number of minutes between updates of the queue statistics table (sQTbl) data. A value of 0 disables gathering of queue related data. Configuration Variable: QueTimer Set-requests: Take effect on next timer expiration Changes to this value are written to the sCfgFile.

sCfgDskMinFreeBlks.name: sCfgDskMinFreeBlks
sCfgDskMinFreeBlks.description: The minimum number of disk blocks that must be free on a disk. When the number of free blocks on a disk drops below this level, excessive disk utilization (sDskFull) traps begin to be sent. If this variable is set to a value other than zero, it is used to determine when to send sDskFull traps for disks not specified in the critical disk table (see sCfgCritDsk). This value and sCfgDskLimit are mutually exclusive, i.e., only one of these values is in effect at any given time. If neither value is specified in the configuration file, then the default value of sCfgDskLimit is used for disk monitoring and sCfgDskMinFreeBlks is set to zero. To disable default disk full monitoring, both of these values must be zero. Set-requests to this value will fail unless sCfgDskLimit is set to zero. Configuration Variable: DskMinFreeBlks Set-requests: Take effect immediately Changes to this value are written to the sCfgFile.

sCfgMemLimit.name: sCfgMemLimit
sCfgMemLimit.description: The percentage of physical memory utilization at which excessive memory utilization (sMemFull) traps begin to be sent. A value of 0 disables these traps. Configuration Variable: MemUse Set-requests: Take effect immediately Changes to this value are written to the sCfgFile.

sCfgCOMQueueLimit.name: sCfgCOMQueueLimit
sCfgCOMQueueLimit.description: The number of processes in COM state at which excessive compute queue (sCOMQue) traps begin to be sent. A value of 0 disables these traps. Configuration Variable: COMQueue Set-requests: Take effect immediately Changes to this value are written to the sCfgFile.

sCfgCOMOQueueLimit.name: sCfgCOMOQueueLimit
sCfgCOMOQueueLimit.description: The number of processes in COMO state at which excessive outswapped compute queue (sCOMOQue) traps begin to be sent. A value of 0 disables these traps. Configuration Variable: COMOQueue Set-requests: Take effect immediately Changes to this value are written to the sCfgFile.

sCfgOpcomCards.description: Flag which determines if NM*SysMgr will receive opcom CARDS class messages. Setting this variable to disabled(2) disables NM*SysMgr from receiving CARDS opcom messages. Configuration Variable: Cards Set-requests: Take effect on next process start-up Changes to this value are written to the sCfgFile.

Setting this variable to disabled(2) disables NM*SysMgr from receiving PRINTER opcom messages. sCfgOpcomFilter.name: sCfgOpcomFilter
sCfgOpcomFilter.description: Flag which determines if NM*SysMgr will drop opcom messages that match filter criteria or drop all opcom messages except those that match filter criteria. Configuration Variable: Filter Set-requests: Take effect on next process start-up Changes to this value are written to the sCfgFile.

sCfgLocalDisksOnly.name: sCfgLocalDisksOnly
sCfgLocalDisksOnly.description: Flag which may be used to instruct NM*SysMgr to gather disk statistics either on all available disks or only on local disks. A disk is considered to be local if the variable sDskRemote for the disk is FALSE(2), indicating that the disk is not remote. If this flag is set to TRUE(1), the disk table (sDskTbl) will only contain data on local disks. If this flag is set to FALSE(2), the disk table (sDskTbl) will contain data on all available disks. Configuration Variable: LocalDisksOnly Set-requests: Take effect on next timer expiration Changes to this value are written to the sCfgFile.

sCfgCritDisksOnly.name: sCfgCritDisksOnly
sCfgCritDisksOnly.description: Flag which may be used to instruct NM*SysMgr to gather disk statistics either on all available disks or only on disks listed in the Critical Disk file (COMTEK$SYSMGR_CRITDSK). If this flag is set to TRUE(1), the disk table (sDskTbl) will only contain data on disks listed in the Critical Disk file. If this flag is set to FALSE(2), the disk table (sDskTbl) will contain data on all available disks. Configuration Variable: CritDisksOnly Set-requests: Take effect on next timer expiration Changes to this value are written to the sCfgFile.

vmsModeUpdateTime.name: vmsModeUpdateTime
vmsModeUpdateTime.description: Time when CPU mode statistics were last gathered.

vmsModeUpdateInterval.name: vmsModeUpdateInterval
vmsModeUpdateInterval.description: How often CPU mode statistics are to be gathered. A value of 0 disables gathering of CPU mode statistics. This value is expressed in minutes.

vmsModeCpuCount.name: vmsModeCpuCount
vmsModeCpuCount.description: Number of entries in the CPU Mode table (i.e., the number of CPUs being monitored).

vmsModeCpuId.name: vmsModeCpuId
vmsModeCpuId.description: CPU ID for mode data in this row in the mode table.

vmsModeKernel.name: vmsModeKernel
vmsModeKernel.description: Number of clock ticks this CPU has spent in kernel mode (excluding interrupt stack time) since the system was booted.

vmsModeExec.name: vmsModeExec
vmsModeExec.description: Number of clock ticks this CPU has spent in Executive mode since the system was booted.

vmsModeSuper.name: vmsModeSuper
vmsModeSuper.description: Number of clock ticks this CPU has spent in Supervisor mode since the system was booted.

vmsModeUser.name: vmsModeUser
vmsModeUser.description: Number of clock ticks this CPU has spent in User mode (excluding compatibility-mode time) since the system was booted.

vmsModeInter.name: vmsModeInter
vmsModeInter.description: Number of clock ticks (10-millisecond units) this CPU has spent on the Interrupt stack since the system was booted.

vmsModeMPSync.name: vmsModeMPSync
vmsModeMPSync.description: Number of clock ticks this CPU has spent synchronizing multiple CPUs since the system was booted.

vmsModeCompat.name: vmsModeCompat
vmsModeCompat.description: Number of clock ticks this CPU has spent in Compatibility mode since the system was booted.

vmsModeIdle.name: vmsModeIdle
vmsModeIdle.description: Number of clock ticks this CPU has spent executing the NULL process since the system was booted.

vmsTotalKernel.name: vmsTotalKernel
vmsTotalKernel.description: Total number of clock ticks all CPUs have spent in kernel mode (excluding interrupt stack time) since the system was booted.

vmsTotalExec.name: vmsTotalExec
vmsTotalExec.description: Total clock ticks all CPUs have spent in Executive mode since the system was booted.

vmsTotalSuper.name: vmsTotalSuper
vmsTotalSuper.description: Total clock ticks all CPUs have spent in Supervisor mode since the system was booted.

vmsTotalUser.name: vmsTotalUser
vmsTotalUser.description: Total clock ticks all CPUs have spent in User mode (excluding compatibility-mode time) since the system was booted.

vmsTotalInter.name: vmsTotalInter
vmsTotalInter.description: Total clock ticks (10-millisecond units) all CPUs have spent on the Interrupt stack since the system was booted.

vmsTotalMPSync.name: vmsTotalMPSync
vmsTotalMPSync.description: Total clock ticks all CPUs have spent synchronizing multiple CPUs since the system was booted.

vmsTotalComp.name: vmsTotalComp
vmsTotalComp.description: Total clock ticks all CPUs have spent in Compatibility mode since the system was booted.

vmsTotalIdle.name: vmsTotalIdle
vmsTotalIdle.description: Total clock ticks all CPUs have spent executing the NULL process since the system was booted.

vmsFileUpdateTime.name: vmsFileUpdateTime
vmsFileUpdateTime.description: Time when File System statistics were last updated.

vmsFileUpdateInterval.name: vmsFileUpdateInterval
